ionary origin of novel characters, Wagner applies it to the origin and evolution of specific systems, such as cell types; skin, hair, and feathers; limbs and digits; and flowers.The first major synthesis of homology to be published in decades, Homology, Genes, and Evolutionary Innovation reveals how a mechanistically based theory can serve as a unifying concept for any branch of science concerned with the structure and development of organisms, and how it can help explain major transitions in evolution and broad patterns of biological diversity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDevelopmental genetics. 0aEvolution (Biology). 0aGenetic regulation. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Evolution.2bisacsh  aadaptation.  aamniotes.  aangiosperms.  aautopodium.  abiological diversity.  abody parts.  abody plans.  abreasts.  acanalization.  acell fate.  acell type identity.  acell types.  acell typogenesis.  acells.  acharacter identity network.  acharacter identity.  acharacter origination.  acharacter states.  acharacters.  acis-regulatory elements.  aclass.  acommon ancestor.  acommon ancestry.  acryptic genetic variation.  adevelopment.  adevelopmental biology.  adevelopmental evolution.  adevelopmental genetics.  adevelopmental mechanisms.  adevelopmental pathways.  adevelopmental types.  adevelopmental variation.  adevo-evo research.  adigit identity.  adigit loss.  adigits.  aembryonic stem cells.  aevolution.  aevolutionary biology.  aevolutionary developmental biology.  aevolutionary novelties.  afeathers.  afins.  afinЬimb transition.  aflower development.  aflower organ identity.  aflower organs.  aflowers.  afunctional specialization.  afunctionalism.  agene duplication.  agene expression.  agene regulatory network